### **(1) Translation of the Story into English**

**魏武侯謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，退朝而有喜色。**  
King Wei of Wei was deliberating on state affairs and made the right decisions, so that none of his ministers could match him. After court, he had a look of joy on his face.

**吳起進曰：「亦嘗有以楚莊王之語，聞於左右者乎？」**  
Wu Qi stepped forward and said, "Have you ever heard the words of King Zhuang of Chu spoken to those around you?"

**武侯曰：「楚莊王之語何如？」**  
King Wei replied, "What did King Zhuang of Chu say?"

**吳起對曰：「楚莊王謀事而當，群臣莫逮，退朝而有憂色。申公巫臣進問曰：『王朝而有憂色，何也？』莊王曰：『不穀謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，是以憂也。其在中蘬之言也，曰：「諸侯自為得師者王，得友者霸，得疑者存，自為謀而莫己若者亡。」』**  
Wu Qi replied, "King Zhuang of Chu, when he deliberated on state affairs and made the right decisions, yet after court had a look of worry on his face. Minister Shen Gong Wuchen asked, 'Your Majesty, why do you have a worried look after court?' The king replied, 'I, the unworthy one, deliberate on state affairs and make the right decisions, yet none of my ministers can match me. That is why I am worried. It is as the saying goes: "A ruler who has ministers who can be his teachers becomes a king; one who has ministers who can be his equals becomes a hegemon; one who has ministers who can be his doubts becomes a ruler who barely survives; one who deliberates alone and finds no one to match him will lose his state."'

**今以不穀之不肖，而群臣莫能逮，吾國幾於亡乎！是以憂也。』**  
"Now, because I am unworthy, and none of my ministers can match me, my state is almost lost! That is why I am worried."

**楚莊王以憂，而君以喜。**  
King Zhuang of Chu was worried, but you, my lord, are joyful.

**武侯逡巡再拜曰：「天使夫子振寡人之過也。」**  
King Wei stepped back and bowed twice, saying, "Heaven has sent you, my teacher, to correct my faults."

